    <h1>Diffusion Tensor Imaging (DTI) </h1>
    <h2>Introduction</h2>
    <p>
    The isotropic free diffusion model proposed by Fick and later Einstein, is not accurate to model water diffusion through complex biological structures in the brain. Diffusion Tensor Model proposed by [ref author] is a direct
        extension of the (scalar) isotropic model : Diffusion is considered anisotropic; three orthogonal diffusion directions are selected, diffusion in other directions are obtained as a trilinear combination
        of these three orthogonal directions. The mathematical object used to describe this behaviour is a 2 order-rank tensor (in this case a covariance matrix) thus Diffusion Tensor Imaging (DTI).
      </p>
      <p> There is a abundant methodological litterature about DTI, whether it is about robust estimation of the tensor coefficients,
          interpolation, calculation and interpretation of derived parameters. See Emsell, L., Van Hecke, W., and Tournier, J. D. (2016). Introduction to diffusion tensor imaging. In Diffusion Tensor Imaging (pp. 7-19). Springer New York. for an up to date review.</p>
      <h2> DTI in Diffuse </h2>
      <p>Diffuse allows the user to:<ul>
          <li><i>estimate diffusion tensor coefficients</i> using several methods <a href="bvprocess://DTI_tensor_model"><bvProcessName name="DTI_tensor_model"/></a> <a href="bvshowprocess://DTI_tensor_model"><img src="../../images/icons/icon_process.png" border="0"/></a></li>,
          <li> <i>calculate derived indices</i> such as Fractionnal Anisotropy <a href="bvprocess://DTI_derived_indices"><bvProcessName name="DTI_derived_indices"/></a> <a href="bvshowprocess://DTI_derived_indices"><img src="../../images/icons/icon_process.png" border="0"/></a></li>
          <li> compute <i>diffusion Orientation Distribution</i> <a href="bvprocess://DTI_ODF"><bvProcessName name="DTI_ODF"/></a> <a href="bvshowprocess://DTI_ODF"><img src="../../images/icons/icon_process.png" border="0"/></a></li>.
      </ul>
      </p>.
